<TITLE> US court rules against accused Nazi guard Demjanjuk </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 CHICAGO, Jan 30 (bdnews24.com/Reuters) - An appeals court on Wednesday ruled against accused Nazi guard John Demjanjuk, saying a US immigration judge had the authority to order the retired Ohio auto worker deported to his native Ukraine. The decision from the Cincinnati-based US Court of Appeals for the 6th Circuit brings the 87-year-old Demjanjuk's 30-year-long legal battle nearer to an end. His lawyers had said before Wednesday's ruling that they would pursue their appeal to the US Supreme Court. Demjanjuk was once wrongly convicted of being the sadistic Nazi death camp guard "Ivan the Terrible" and sentenced to death in Israel. The Israeli Supreme Court later overturned the conviction, saying another man was probably "Ivan," a sadistic guard at the Treblinka death camp where 870,000 people died. But US officials stripped him of his citizenship again in 2002, ruling that he had worked as a guard at three other death camps
